systems, from miniature devices to full-scale industrial plants. Focusing on the macroscopic realm, this paper reviews principles and pathways for intensifying industrial processes, starting with a core reaction-separation-recycle process structure and continuing with energy-integrated systems. An emphasis is placed on describing the interplay between economic, safety and environmental benefits, and the constraints and demands that intensification places on process design and process control by reducing the respective available degrees of freedom. Specific application examples are introduced to support these ideas. The paper concludes with an account of potential future development directions for theory and applications. Â© 2014 Elsevier B.V.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84904303113" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84904303113&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84904303113%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60013372" id="60013372"><affilname>University of Texas at Austin</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="7801529672" seq="1"><ce:initials>M.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Baldea M.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Baldea</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Michael</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>M.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Baldea M.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Baldea</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Michael</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/7801529672</author-url><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60013372" id="60013372"/></author></authors></abstracts-retrieval-response>
